        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Down Farnborough | Kent</placeName>
                    <date>Nov. 19<hi rend="superscript">th</hi></date>
                    <salute>My dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                    
<p>I am very much obliged for your note of the 13<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>. &amp; I write now merely, in answer to your query, to say that I will of course leave the month of February to you for looking out for an investment for me, &amp; I much hope that you may succeed.<ref target="#foot.f1"/></p>
<p>I remain, dear Sir | yours sincerely | C. Darwin<lb resp="#mjhawkins"/></p>
<p rend="left">T. Salt. Esq<hi rend="superscript">re</hi>—</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">Salt’s letter has not been found, but see this volume, Supplement, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-1269F.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to Thomas Salt, 12 November [1849]</ref>. CD had asked Salt to look out for a new investment for some money that he expected to be repaid to him in March 1850.</note>
        </div>        
            
